               <head>Copies of contracts in Demotic Egyptian and Greek.</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Copies of three sales contracts by three funerary priests (coachytes),
                     Teephibis, Hasos and Pechutes, all relatives buying different parts of the same
                     property in Thebes.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="egy-Egyd" otherLangs="grc">
                     Egyptian in Demotic script; Greek signatures and abstracts
                  </textLang>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="scroll">
                     <supportDesc material="papyrus">
                        <support/>
                        <extent>A complete papyrus roll written along the fibres with the back being
                           blank. The papyrus is mounted on paper and housed in one glass cases.
                              <dimensions type="reconstructed" unit="mm">
                              <height>300</height>
                              <width>790</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>Written along the fibres in 3 columns in Demotic Egyptian with a
                           Greek subscriptions written above each of the columns, the back is
                           probably blank. </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>Likely written by one scribe for Demotic and another hand for the
                        Greek.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>



               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="-0153" notAfter="-0146">153-146
                        BC</origDate></origin>
                  <provenance>Possibly from <ref type="place_7001297">Thebes</ref>. Purchased by
                     Colonel Valentine Patrick Terrell Vivian in Egypt around 1882 and bequeathed to
                     his brother-in-law the Reverend Vivian Eccles Skrine. </provenance>
                  <acquisition>Given to the Bodleian by the Reverend Vivian Eccles Skrine
                     (1850-1925), 30 March 1913.</acquisition>
               </history>
